Sleeping Tracker App
This is the repository for the Sleeping Tracker app, a web application to track your sleep duration and daily ratings.

Frontend Setup
Follow these steps to run the frontend of the Sleeping Tracker app on your local machine:

Prerequisites
Node.js: Make sure you have Node.js installed on your machine. You can download it from the official website: https://nodejs.org/
Clone the Repository
Open a terminal or command prompt on your local machine.

Run the following command to clone the repository:


git clone Sleeping_Tracker_Final.git
Install Dependencies
Change into the frontend directory:

cd sleeping-tracker/frontend
Install the project dependencies:

npm install


Run the Development Server
Start the development server:


npm run dev
The frontend should now be running on http://localhost:3000.
Access the App
Open your web browser and navigate to http://localhost:3000 to access the Sleeping Tracker app.

Backend Setup

Follow these steps to run the backend of the Sleeping Tracker app on your local machine:

Prerequisites
Node.js: Make sure you have Node.js installed on your machine. You can download it from the official website: https://nodejs.org/

PostgreSQL: Install PostgreSQL on your machine and create a database for the app. You can download PostgreSQL from: https://www.postgresql.org/

Clone the Repository
Open a terminal or command prompt on your local machine.

Run the following command to clone the repository:




Change into the backend directory:

cd sleeping-tracker/backend
Install the project dependencies:
npm install

Configure Environment Variables


Open the .env file in a text editor and set the environment variables according to your local configuration. For example:

DATABASE_URL=postgres://username:password@localhost:5432/sleep_tracker_db
Replace postgres://username:password@localhost:5432/sleep_tracker_db with your PostgreSQL database connection URL.

Run Database Migrations
Run the database migrations to set up the database schema:
npm run migrate

Start the Backend Server
node index

The backend should now be running on http://localhost:8080/api/sleep-records.
Test the API Endpoints
You can use tools like Postman or curl to test the API endpoints. For example, to get all sleep records, send a GET request to http://localhost:8080/api/sleep-records..
